The paper proposes practical algorithms for computing treecut width and treedepth, which are width parameters that have gained recent attention in the theoretical research community. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. Additionally, the paper proposes an approach based on propositional satisfiability (SAT) and characterisations based on sequences of partitions, which are techniques commonly used in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves experimental testing on benchmark instances, which could fall under Computational Complexity (cs.CC) or Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM).
